Introduction\
Data preprocessing is a crucial step before applying machine learning algorithms. In Weka, preprocessing ensures data quality, improves model performance, and removes inconsistencies. Classification, on the other hand, is a supervised learning method used to predict labels based on historical data.\
\
Why Preprocessing Matters?\
Raw data often contains missing values, noise, duplicate records, and irrelevant features. If not handled properly, these issues can lead to poor model accuracy.\
\
Preprocessing Steps in Weka\
	1.	Loading the Dataset\
	\'95	Open Weka \uc0\u8594  Select Explorer \u8594  Load data from CSV, ARFF, or database.\
	2.	Handling Missing Values\
	\'95	Use the Replace Missing Values filter to fill missing attributes.\
	\'95	Example: Filling missing age values in a dataset using the mean age.\
	3.	Attribute Selection\
	\'95	Use Weka\'92s Attribute Selection filter to remove irrelevant features.\
	\'95	Example: Removing \'93Customer ID\'94 from a purchase dataset as it does not influence buying patterns.\
	4.	Data Normalization\
	\'95	Ensures all numerical values are on a similar scale.\
	\'95	Example: Min-max scaling transforms income values from different ranges to 0-1.\
\
Applying Classification in Weka\
	1.	Select Classification Algorithm\
	\'95	In the Classify tab, choose a classification algorithm like Na\'efve Bayes, Decision Tree, or SVM.\
	2.	Split the Dataset\
	\'95	Use 70-30 training/testing split or cross-validation.\
	3.	Train the Model\
	\'95	Click Start to train the model on the dataset.\
	4.	Evaluate Performance\
	\'95	Check accuracy, precision, recall, and confusion matrix in Weka\'92s output.\
\
